<section class="manifesto shell section" id="about">
  <p class="eyebrow reveal">01 — How I think</p>
  <p class="statement reveal">I don't build features.<br/><em>I solve business problems</em><br/>through technology.</p>

  <div class="about-content reveal">
    <figure class="portrait-wrap">
      <img src="/images/hero-bg-2.jpeg" alt="MD Mehedi Hasan Rakib" width="1200" height="1200" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <span>MD Mehedi Hasan Rakib</span>
        <span>Dhaka, Bangladesh</span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <div class="about-right">
      <div class="about-grid">
        <p>I started my career building websites. But I soon learned that a successful product is not just about good code—it must solve a real problem for the people and businesses using it.</p>
        <p>Over the last 4+ years, I have grown from a frontend developer into a Product Engineer. Today, I turn ideas and business needs into complete products across web, mobile, ecommerce, and AI.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="about-extended reveal">
        I combine business thinking, user experience, and engineering to build products that are simple, useful, and ready for real users. I have launched a public Shopify app, an Android application, an AI virtual try-on, and several production platforms. Every project begins with one question: <em>what problem are we solving?</em>
      </p>
      <ul class="about-values reveal">
        <li>Understand the Problem</li>
        <li>Design for People</li>
        <li>Build for Real Use</li>
        <li>Business Value</li>
        <li>Own the Outcome</li>
        <li>Keep Improving</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="about-why reveal">
    <div class="about-why-grid">
      <h3>Why Product<br/>Engineering?</h3>
      <div class="about-why-text">
        <p>Because features don't move businesses forward—products do. Product engineering means owning the full journey: understanding the business problem, designing the experience, writing the code, shipping to production, and measuring what actually changed.</p>
        <p>I chose this path because I've seen what happens when design and engineering are separated from business intent. You get beautiful products that don't solve anything, and functional code that nobody uses. Product engineering is the discipline that closes that gap.</p>
        <div class="about-philosophy">
          <p>The question is never <em>"can we build this?"</em><br/>It's always <em>"should we, and why?"</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

